# Implementation of Multilingual Support in Moka-Chat

The goal is to apply the user's default language (from the backend `adm_user` table) and use the translation files located in `public/lang/*/titles.js` to localize the React chat application.

## Open Questions

> [!WARNING]
> The existing translation files (`titles.js`) are formatted as raw JS object properties (e.g., `key : "value",` without `{}`) and contain JS comments, meaning they cannot be imported or parsed natively as JSON.
> 
> My plan is to write a one-time Node.js script to automatically parse all of them and convert them into standard `.json` files (`public/lang/*/titles.json`). This is the safest and most standard way to load translations in a React app. Does this sound good to you?

## Proposed Changes

---

### Scripts

I will add a utility script to convert the files.

#### [NEW] `scripts/convert_lang.js`
A script that reads `public/lang/*/titles.js`, extracts the key-value pairs, and saves them as `public/lang/*/titles.json`.

---

### Context & State Management

I will create a context to provide translation functions throughout the app.

#### [NEW] `src/context/LanguageContext.js`
- Create a `LanguageProvider` that uses the `language` from the `AuthContext` user object.
- It will `fetch('/lang/{language}/titles.json')` when the user logs in.
- Provides a `t(key)` function that returns the translated string.

#### [MODIFY] `src/context/AuthContext.js`
- Ensure the user object in state persists the `language` field.

#### [MODIFY] `src/App.js`
- Pass `mkUser.language` (or default to 'en') into the `login()` function from `window.MokapenChatUser`.
- Wrap the `<ChatWidget />` tree in `<LanguageProvider>`.

